    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
    <title>Structured Instruction</title>
    <p>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>10 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>To formalize the transition from physical measurement to exact mathematical representation using surds.</p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </p>
        <title>Teacher Connection</title>
                <p>
                    <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Emphasize that while measuring tapes give decimal approximations, the "true" mathematical length is often an irrational number. Explain that in high-precision fields, using the exact surd prevents compounding errors.
                </p>
</axiom>
<insight>
        <title>Key Takeaways: Surds in the Real World</title>
        <p>
            Irrational numbers are the blueprint for physical design, maintaining exact proportions where decimals fail.
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        International paper sizes rely on a fixed ratio of <m>\sqrt{2} : 1</m>. This allows paper to be folded perfectly in half (from A4 to A5) without distorting the shape or text scaling.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Real-world infrastructure like bridge trusses or railway supports requires calculating exact diagonals using the Pythagorean theorem. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Using rounded approximations (like <m>1.4</m> instead of <m>\sqrt{2}</m>) creates minor errors that compound over long distances, risking structural failure. Keeping numbers in surd form preserves structural integrity.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </insight>
<!-- <insight>
    <title>Surds: The Invisible Scaffolding of Reality</title>
    <p>
        Irrational numbers are often called the "invisible scaffolding" of our physical world. While we rarely see a ruler marked with <m>\sqrt{2}</m> or <m>\sqrt{5}</m>, these numbers are essential for precision in engineering and nature. For instance, the A4 paper you measured is specifically designed so that the ratio of its sides is <m>\sqrt{2}:1</m>; this ensures that when you fold the paper in half to make an A5 sheet, the proportions remain identical, allowing for easy scaling of text and images.
    </p>
    <p>
        In Kenyan infrastructure, such as the construction of the Standard Gauge Railway or modern bridges in Nairobi, engineers must calculate diagonal supports using the Pythagorean theorem. If they only used rounded decimals (like 1.4 instead of <m>\sqrt{2}</m>), those tiny errors would compound over long distances, potentially leading to structural misalignment or failure. Beyond construction, surds appear in the physics of falling objects and the frequencies of musical notes. Understanding irrational numbers transitions a learner from "estimating" the world to "precisely defining" it, a key skill for any aspiring STEM professional.
    </p>
</insight> -->

